WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.730
&gt;&gt; For those who don't know me, I'm Mark.
I'm part of the @Google team.

00:00:03.730 --> 00:00:10.250
I have to admit, I was a little bit hesitant
about today's talk.

00:00:10.250 --> 00:00:14.570
I'm one of these people who thinks of computer
gamers as these sort of

00:00:14.570 --> 00:00:17.560
teenaged troglodytes who heroically contribute
to the obesity crisis

00:00:17.560 --> 00:00:18.700
rather than sort of as deeply social people
but I'm here to be proved

00:00:18.700 --> 00:00:23.440
wrong, which is great.
So welcome, of course, Tom Chatfield who is

00:00:23.440 --> 00:00:30.860
here to prove me wrong.
Tom has written this book Fun, Inc., and is

00:00:30.860 --> 00:00:36.940
going to tell us all about
the social and business side of gaming, so

00:00:36.940 --> 00:00:39.810
please welcome him.
Thanks.

00:00:39.810 --> 00:00:40.810
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:40.810 --> 00:00:46.500
TOM CHATFIELD: Thank you for having me.
I've been to -- I've written a book that covers

00:00:46.500 --> 00:00:49.720
all sorts of different
aspects of gaming, that talks about the social

00:00:49.720 --> 00:00:51.235
aspects of gaming, that
talks about the business aspects of gaming,

00:00:51.235 --> 00:00:53.510
that talks about even games
in artistic terms.

00:00:53.510 --> 00:00:58.110
But I wanted to talk with something specific.
One of the things that I think is one of the

00:00:58.110 --> 00:01:01.610
most interesting key
points and key ways of thinking about games

00:01:01.610 --> 00:01:05.840
in general -- video games
in particular -- which is, games as learning

00:01:05.840 --> 00:01:08.579
engines, games as learning
experiences.

00:01:08.579 --> 00:01:13.500
I've called it the fail epic.
Partly because I think one of the key aspects

00:01:13.500 --> 00:01:18.590
of games is the way that
they transform our attitude towards failure,

00:01:18.590 --> 00:01:23.409
the idea of failure, with
that, the idea of success.

00:01:23.409 --> 00:01:27.130
I think there are really two key points about
all games which underpin

00:01:27.130 --> 00:01:30.069
the fact that games have a history as old
as civilization.

00:01:30.069 --> 00:01:33.340
In the first place, games in many ways, precede
civilization.

00:01:33.340 --> 00:01:37.759
And this is the fact that games touch something
very fundamental in us

00:01:37.759 --> 00:01:41.729
by being both concentrated kinds of experience
and safe kinds of

00:01:41.729 --> 00:01:44.369
experience.
So quintessential games, historically, were

00:01:44.369 --> 00:01:47.829
to do with warfare and to
do with social hierarchy.

00:01:47.829 --> 00:01:52.179
That these were safe, concentrated, repetitive
ways of honing absolutely

00:01:52.179 --> 00:01:56.299
vital skills, but skills that would get you
killed if you tried to

00:01:56.299 --> 00:02:00.041
practice them by just going out and doing
them.

00:02:00.041 --> 00:02:03.619
So games offer a safe, concentrated environment
and the structure of

00:02:03.619 --> 00:02:07.520
incentives and rewards to keep people doing
these things and

00:02:07.520 --> 00:02:10.989
practicing, getting better at these absolutely
vital skills.

00:02:10.989 --> 00:02:15.540
And in many ways, computer games are intensification
of this, of the

00:02:15.540 --> 00:02:20.720
key things they offer to games in general
is the kind of feedback you

00:02:20.720 --> 00:02:25.579
get is far, far more rapid and the kind of
control that you have over

00:02:25.579 --> 00:02:31.209
the experience that you get from it is far,
far more precise than

00:02:31.209 --> 00:02:35.494
anything we've seen before.
Start off with a cheerful quote from Samuel

00:02:35.494 --> 00:02:37.530
Beckett.
This really is about the idea of recasting

00:02:37.530 --> 00:02:39.540
failure, not as an absolute
-- you failed, therefore it's all over.

00:02:39.540 --> 00:02:46.010
It's about recasting failure as something
that you do better.

00:02:46.010 --> 00:02:52.610
It's a step on the way to success.
And this, I think, gets at one of the key

00:02:52.610 --> 00:02:56.830
points about all games which
is transforming failure, I think video games

00:02:56.830 --> 00:03:00.740
are doing this in sort of
a particularly intense and remarkable way.

00:03:00.740 --> 00:03:05.500
A slightly different quote.
I'm not quite sure what metric Woody Allen

00:03:05.500 --> 00:03:07.810
was using to arrive at his
statistic.

00:03:07.810 --> 00:03:12.280
But I think he's hit on something there, by
far the most common form of

00:03:12.280 --> 00:03:15.019
failure is not trying.
By far the most common form of failure is

00:03:15.019 --> 00:03:20.390
not being prepared to engage
in a task in the first place, because it's

00:03:20.390 --> 00:03:23.359
intimidating, because of the
risk of censure.

00:03:23.359 --> 00:03:27.049
Because it's -- if you're worried about how
something will go, if the

00:03:27.049 --> 00:03:30.930
result is something that scares you, you're
unlikely to brave it or

00:03:30.930 --> 00:03:35.650
take it on.
Now, we're talking about video games as learning

00:03:35.650 --> 00:03:39.079
engines.
I'm not talking about taking video games and

00:03:39.079 --> 00:03:40.239
putting them into
classrooms.

00:03:40.239 --> 00:03:45.700
It's not about using Pac-Man to teach Spanish.
It's not about saying that everyone in a history

00:03:45.700 --> 00:03:49.719
class ought to be
playing Age of Empires in order to learn about

00:03:49.719 --> 00:03:52.129
history.
I think that kind of argument misses the point

00:03:52.129 --> 00:03:57.650
because what games are
doing is showing us some very powerful, underlying

00:03:57.650 --> 00:04:02.010
human principles
about learning and about structures of learning.

00:04:02.010 --> 00:04:05.719
And what's been remarkable over the 50-odd
years that computer games

00:04:05.719 --> 00:04:09.489
have existed is that they haven't stood still,
they didn't just arrive

00:04:09.489 --> 00:04:14.709
in the world as addictive, compelling, fully-formed
activities.

00:04:14.709 --> 00:04:19.810
They began as one thing, and then because
of commercial and social

00:04:19.810 --> 00:04:23.630
pressures, they have followed an incredibly
rapid evolutionary curve,

00:04:23.630 --> 00:04:28.810
next to their authors, in terms of engaging
people, in terms of

00:04:28.810 --> 00:04:32.120
incrementally improving the kind of engagement
they offer.

00:04:32.120 --> 00:04:34.740
And I want to look at the underlying lessons
that come from it.

00:04:34.740 --> 00:04:40.350
First of all, talk a little bit about traditional
learning and

00:04:40.350 --> 00:04:44.390
training.
Now, this is a bit of a cliche to say that

00:04:44.390 --> 00:04:50.520
traditional learning and
training has stood still for sort of hundreds

00:04:50.520 --> 00:04:52.910
of years.
It's certainly true that we have a very schizophrenic

00:04:52.910 --> 00:04:58.480
attitude towards
play and towards play-like activities.

00:04:58.480 --> 00:05:03.670
And we absolutely accept that up to the ages
of 5 or 6 the bulk of the

00:05:03.670 --> 00:05:07.510
way that people learn about the world around
them is by sort of

00:05:07.510 --> 00:05:11.760
playful, unstructured or game-like activities
and then suddenly we do a

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:14.660
switch.
We insist that the hard work begins.

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:18.960
And we begin what you could sum up as a rather
linear, straight-forward

00:05:18.960 --> 00:05:22.570
process of learning.
And there have been plenty of efforts to change

00:05:22.570 --> 00:05:25.740
this to a form to
introduce group work, a lot of these have

00:05:25.740 --> 00:05:29.810
been very effective.
But they haven't really, I think, had underlying

00:05:29.810 --> 00:05:33.040
principles rooted in
empirical study, what people are actually

00:05:33.040 --> 00:05:37.340
like.
So I want to talk about a few of the sort

00:05:37.340 --> 00:05:41.770
of cliche limitations of
traditional attitudes towards learning approach.

00:05:41.770 --> 00:05:52.140
There we have a traditional learning scene.
So first thing is few failures; they're not

00:05:52.140 --> 00:05:54.520
experimental.
Now I don't mean that people aren't failing.

00:05:54.520 --> 00:05:58.350
In fact, if you think of learning as being
something that's truly

00:05:58.350 --> 00:06:01.740
tested by what it does for the weakest members
of the group, and if you

00:06:01.740 --> 00:06:06.620
imagine a weak 6- or 7-year old struggling
to learn to read a passage

00:06:06.620 --> 00:06:10.600
in fact, their experience in traditional lesson
is likely to be almost

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:15.400
entirely composed of failure.
There will probably be three or four decisive

00:06:15.400 --> 00:06:19.460
failures, at which point
someone is very likely to give up.

00:06:19.460 --> 00:06:23.910
What it isn't is experimental, and what they're
not being given is

00:06:23.910 --> 00:06:28.920
opportunities to fail in a positive way.
They will simply try to stumble through a

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:33.040
few sentences, stop, and
really be able to go no further.

00:06:33.040 --> 00:06:39.240
There's no control they have over it.
And it makes the second point, that there's

00:06:39.240 --> 00:06:41.580
a lot of censure associated
with this kind of failure.

00:06:41.580 --> 00:06:46.530
It's pain not gain from these sorts of things.
When confronted the sheet they're supposed

00:06:46.530 --> 00:06:49.670
to be reading, and words
don't make sense to them in the classroom,

00:06:49.670 --> 00:06:53.010
there is humiliation.
There is frustration.

00:06:53.010 --> 00:06:55.840
There's a big turn off.
There's not really that much else.

00:06:55.840 --> 00:07:00.060
And the feedback is very slow.
I think it's still true especially for weaker

00:07:00.060 --> 00:07:03.900
people that often when
some people sit down to their duty the first

00:07:03.900 --> 00:07:10.260
or second time they
actually sat for an exam, the feedback they

00:07:10.260 --> 00:07:12.440
get takes a long time to
come.

00:07:12.440 --> 00:07:16.280
It can seem very distant from what they're
doing and seem very

00:07:16.280 --> 00:07:20.090
incomprehensible and threatening.
And I think this applies just as much to a

00:07:20.090 --> 00:07:22.970
lot of training
environments, implicitly or explicitly, that

00:07:22.970 --> 00:07:25.290
feedback is delivered in
big, ugly, rather unpleasant lumps.

00:07:25.290 --> 00:07:29.130
And there's little personal investment.
By that I mean that someone doesn't have much

00:07:29.130 --> 00:07:31.040
control over the process
they're going through.

00:07:31.040 --> 00:07:37.280
If you imagine a person reading the textbook,
it's like the books

00:07:37.280 --> 00:07:42.140
dumped on your desk -- work through it.
You don't really have much of an option to

00:07:42.140 --> 00:07:43.940
choose anything to this
process.

00:07:43.940 --> 00:07:45.560
You will submit to it.
You may succeed.

00:07:45.560 --> 00:07:51.610
You may master it; you may not.
But really, it puts an enormous onus on teaching

00:07:51.610 --> 00:07:54.240
you and on your
support structures, and an enormous onus on

00:07:54.240 --> 00:07:59.760
your resourcefulness, but
it's not something you feel you can own in

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:05.870
any sort of a crucial way.
Part and central to this is, I think largely

00:08:05.870 --> 00:08:10.100
true of most conventional training and teaching
that there is one thing that you're doing

00:08:10.100 --> 00:08:13.780
at a time in front of you on the desk, and
task at the moment.

00:08:13.780 --> 00:08:17.420
You may switch to another, but there's a single
path through it, and you

00:08:17.420 --> 00:08:19.590
know with lots of people with a whole spectrum
of abilities, it's

00:08:19.590 --> 00:08:26.510
almost a given that a lot of people will let
down by one way or nothing.

00:08:26.510 --> 00:08:31.890
And re-connected to that history and progress,
so we've got our

00:08:31.890 --> 00:08:35.380
person sitting down in a classroom studying
a piece of reading.

00:08:35.380 --> 00:08:39.450
Now that teacher knows very well what the
syllabus is and probably has

00:08:39.450 --> 00:08:44.130
a very good idea of where all their peoples
sit on the spectrum of are

00:08:44.130 --> 00:08:47.460
they going to pass this exam at the end the
term.

00:08:47.460 --> 00:08:49.330
But they don't really know much about this
at all.

00:08:49.330 --> 00:08:52.400
They have very, very little grasp, even the
good ones, of where they

00:08:52.400 --> 00:08:56.070
need to be eventually, of how long along that
path they are, and of

00:08:56.070 --> 00:08:59.580
where they've come from.
They might have a few scattered results and

00:08:59.580 --> 00:09:02.690
grades, but really -- and
again, I'd say you get this in training environments

00:09:02.690 --> 00:09:07.180
as well, people
don't often have a precise grip on where they

00:09:07.180 --> 00:09:11.040
need to be in the future
-- in a month, in two months, in three months'

00:09:11.040 --> 00:09:16.460
time or any sense of
exactly how far in the year I've done this

00:09:16.460 --> 00:09:20.880
or I've done that.
And this leads to limited peer relationships.

00:09:20.880 --> 00:09:25.610
By which I mean, people tend to be very aware
of where they are on a

00:09:25.610 --> 00:09:28.180
hierarchy, compared to people around them
in the classroom.

00:09:28.180 --> 00:09:32.380
The absolutely sure that you know by the age
of 6 or 7, someone's quite

00:09:32.380 --> 00:09:37.100
aware of where they sit in the pecking order
of who is the top and who

00:09:37.100 --> 00:09:41.210
the middle and who is the bottom.
But you don't have much insight into the process

00:09:41.210 --> 00:09:42.800
that's going on with
your colleagues, particularly in the classroom,

00:09:42.800 --> 00:09:45.240
sitting around you
writing away.

00:09:45.240 --> 00:09:48.420
You have no sense of their method till it
pops out at the end.

00:09:48.420 --> 00:09:51.955
Your interactions with the relationship, tends
to be limited to, if you

00:09:51.955 --> 00:09:59.320
like, competition and worry.
Now video games -- and this is what I thought

00:09:59.320 --> 00:10:01.150
about the trajectory
of games.

00:10:01.150 --> 00:10:03.950
Cause in the beginning games were a bit like
that.

00:10:03.950 --> 00:10:07.430
Yes, when computer games arrived -- I suppose
Space War is the first

00:10:07.430 --> 00:10:11.140
true video game.
They were instantly much more exciting and

00:10:11.140 --> 00:10:12.240
accessible than pretty much
anything that had ever happened on a computer

00:10:12.240 --> 00:10:15.870
before in terms of
sitting down and using them.

00:10:15.870 --> 00:10:19.950
At the same time, they were designed by experts
for experts.

00:10:19.950 --> 00:10:22.980
They were designed largely by male geeks for
other male geeks.

00:10:22.980 --> 00:10:27.260
Even Space Invaders, a very simple game in
some ways, is very, very

00:10:27.260 --> 00:10:29.300
harsh.
It's very, very unforgiving.

00:10:29.300 --> 00:10:33.350
It's frankly very, very difficult.
You have to invest quite a lot in it to get

00:10:33.350 --> 00:10:36.750
anywhere.
You die and you lose your lives.

00:10:36.750 --> 00:10:38.060
That's it.
It's all over.

00:10:38.060 --> 00:10:42.040
You got to start again.
I mean, Asteroids is an absolute nightmare

00:10:42.040 --> 00:10:43.150
trying to get anywhere on
that.

00:10:43.150 --> 00:10:46.240
These early games, they deserve their reputation
as a niche activity

00:10:46.240 --> 00:10:52.830
for teenaged boys who didn't much like the
light because they were so

00:10:52.830 --> 00:10:55.520
difficult in so many ways.
In many ways, learning to master one of these

00:10:55.520 --> 00:10:58.100
games was a traditional
learning experience.

00:10:58.100 --> 00:11:03.700
You had to work at it and some people did.
Some people invested hugely in it.

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:08.280
But that's where they began.
And if they just stayed there, [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:15.610
people said things teenaged
boys, get into them it is a bit of a geek

00:11:15.610 --> 00:11:16.840
and then you grow out of
them, you hope.

00:11:16.840 --> 00:11:17.840
In fact,

00:11:17.840 --> 00:11:20.279
[PAUSE]

00:11:20.279 --> 00:11:24.840
what happened is that games completely transformed
themselves over 30,

00:11:24.840 --> 00:11:26.270
40, 50 years, and staggeringly transformed
themselves.

00:11:26.270 --> 00:11:32.900
I think it's safe to say that electronic games
are now the world's

00:11:32.900 --> 00:11:38.320
largest and fastest growing form of mass participation.
And I believe the largest mass participation

00:11:38.320 --> 00:11:41.270
we've ever known in
history, the word "games" expanded hugely

00:11:41.270 --> 00:11:43.760
to cover a vast spectrum of
activities.

00:11:43.760 --> 00:11:49.600
But I think that there's something to do with
learning that underlies

00:11:49.600 --> 00:11:53.200
almost all the games in the world at the moment,
and that is something

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:54.720
that is evolved through basically the work
of trying to make more

00:11:54.720 --> 00:11:57.290
money, if you like.
Trying to get more people interested in them.

00:11:57.290 --> 00:12:00.760
You got the Space Invaders and a certain kind
of person with a certain

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:05.550
slightly fanatical bent would enjoy playing
it and will try to get high

00:12:05.550 --> 00:12:09.160
scores, but you're missing out on a huge section
of the market.

00:12:09.160 --> 00:12:13.220
And over time, people have tried to bring
in more and more different

00:12:13.220 --> 00:12:17.450
kinds of player.
This obviously is a very nice Flying Mount,

00:12:17.450 --> 00:12:20.080
from I think it's a
forthcoming Flying Mount.

00:12:20.080 --> 00:12:24.560
I think that's going to be in Cataclysms.
I don't think you can get those yet.

00:12:24.560 --> 00:12:28.589
But that's a very nice reward at the end game
of World of Warcraft.

00:12:28.589 --> 00:12:33.750
And you probably know to get to the end game
of Warcraft, not many

00:12:33.750 --> 00:12:35.930
players achieve that, but it's about 12 million
people playing the game

00:12:35.930 --> 00:12:40.710
worldwide, very few of them will make it through
to any really

00:12:40.710 --> 00:12:43.360
high-level ranges.
And yet people keep playing, there are 12

00:12:43.360 --> 00:12:46.550
million people playing this.
And that's because, in many ways, the game

00:12:46.550 --> 00:12:51.730
has replaced the word fail
with a rather different idea.

00:12:51.730 --> 00:12:58.341
And that is not yet succeeded.
By which I mean that the idea of fail at something

00:12:58.341 --> 00:13:02.100
 -- something
censorious, something dreadful, something

00:13:02.100 --> 00:13:05.910
that puts you off so that
80 percent of you don't turn up, as it were.

00:13:05.910 --> 00:13:08.380
80 percent of the world wouldn't bother turning
up to play video games

00:13:08.380 --> 00:13:12.430
in the first place, it's so alienating.
That's been replaced with the recognition

00:13:12.430 --> 00:13:15.540
that you can come up with
things that different players will do.

00:13:15.540 --> 00:13:18.960
Richard Bath, among others, have talked about
four different player

00:13:18.960 --> 00:13:22.440
types which covers pretty much the whole spectrum
of human tendencies:

00:13:22.440 --> 00:13:26.890
People who want to explore, people who want
to achieve, people who want

00:13:26.890 --> 00:13:34.380
to communicate, that sort of thing.
But what we see -- I think Warcraft is a good

00:13:34.380 --> 00:13:39.090
example because it's so
good at combining all the lessons of games

00:13:39.090 --> 00:13:42.530
from the last 40 or
50 years.

00:13:42.530 --> 00:13:45.180
So I want to talk through a little bit about
what it does that is

00:13:45.180 --> 00:13:49.730
drawing and holding in so many different kinds
of people and giving

00:13:49.730 --> 00:13:51.470
them the sense when they're playing that even
though most of them are

00:13:51.470 --> 00:13:53.950
never going to make it into a raid, they're
never going to get Twin

00:13:53.950 --> 00:13:54.950
Blades, they're never going to, you know,
get to the real high-end

00:13:54.950 --> 00:13:55.950
content.
It doesn't feel like failure.

00:13:55.950 --> 00:14:01.339
In many ways it's exciting for them that there
are people who are doing

00:14:01.339 --> 00:14:05.320
that because they've got other stuff to do
which they find rewarding.

00:14:05.320 --> 00:14:11.630
And the interesting thing is, the underpinning
of this, and there we have one of the latest

00:14:11.630 --> 00:14:15.520
versions of this, the idea of achievements,
which

00:14:15.520 --> 00:14:18.890
self-evidently suck in thousands and thousands
of human hours around

00:14:18.890 --> 00:14:23.071
the world.
But what we got is the fact everyone who is

00:14:23.071 --> 00:14:26.250
playing Warcraft is really training for one
thing.

00:14:26.250 --> 00:14:30.810
They're training to control a character, and
click on a whole spectrum

00:14:30.810 --> 00:14:34.950
of different abilities and equip different
items in order to make their

00:14:34.950 --> 00:14:38.650
little character kill stuff.
That's all they're training to do.

00:14:38.650 --> 00:14:42.070
We lose sight of that because there's such
an incredibly elaborate

00:14:42.070 --> 00:14:45.510
network that is going on.
When in fact, we've been trained to do this

00:14:45.510 --> 00:14:49.380
one thing and they've been
trained to do it incredibly well.

00:14:49.380 --> 00:14:54.060
In terms of -- imagine a driving test.
Now the kind of training you get from Warcraft

00:14:54.060 --> 00:14:56.690
is not like learning to
drive a car.

00:14:56.690 --> 00:15:02.910
It's like learning to race an F-1 race.
The level of skill that people are attaining

00:15:02.910 --> 00:15:06.529
from what the game puts
them through, the kind of training they voluntarily

00:15:06.529 --> 00:15:09.560
submit to, indeed
that they pay for, gets people to an incredible

00:15:09.560 --> 00:15:12.720
level of sophistication
and expertise.

00:15:12.720 --> 00:15:16.580
People are very, very, very good at this game.
Lots of them, even somewhat bad at this game,

00:15:16.580 --> 00:15:17.580
is very good at this
game.

00:15:17.580 --> 00:15:20.630
It's incredibly good at getting people to
put in hours of doing

00:15:20.630 --> 00:15:25.960
basically, which is hitting a ball with the
sword.

00:15:25.960 --> 00:15:29.510
And -- it does this because it offers so many
different ways to people

00:15:29.510 --> 00:15:33.170
of making their activity feel like an incremental
success, a

00:15:33.170 --> 00:15:36.960
incremental progress.
First of all, we've got characters at level

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:38.200
70 characters, at the top
there.

00:15:38.200 --> 00:15:42.930
And a little number that you make go up with
