00:31:04.529 --> 00:31:07.580
succeeding, there's also, you mean, this drive
to meet and compare

00:31:07.580 --> 00:31:10.900
yourself to other people.
That's a key factor is that what you're --

00:31:10.900 --> 00:31:16.039
&gt;&gt; I just mean that it's not as simple as
going from not failing to

00:31:16.039 --> 00:31:19.090
not yet succeeding.
That's there kind of a human instinct to succeed

00:31:19.090 --> 00:31:21.639
through defeating
other people which may be missed and there

00:31:21.639 --> 00:31:47.659
is an aside to this.

00:31:47.659 --> 00:32:27.659
TOM CHATFIELD: Yes, I think

00:32:27.659 --> 00:32:29.980
so.
I think absolutely that the social context

00:32:29.980 --> 00:32:31.840
is, is really what drives
it.

00:32:31.840 --> 00:32:35.889
What gives it a point in one sense, there's
little point in sort of --

00:32:35.889 --> 00:32:42.570
and I think defeating other people is a very
strong way of putting it

00:32:42.570 --> 00:32:47.999
-- because I think that games are very good
at rephrasing that as

00:32:47.999 --> 00:32:51.899
another one of these ongoing tasks.
So, yes, you build up your, you know, your

00:32:51.899 --> 00:32:54.649
 -- your kills in Halo, but
